1. 1.Introduction

As one of the most well-known climate phenomenon, El Niño–Southern Oscillation (ENSO) is an irregular periodical variation in winds and sea surface temperatures over the tropical eastern Pacific Ocean. Traditional numerical simulations build upon human expertise in defining events based on subjective thresholds of relevant physical variables. Often, multiple competing methods produce vastly different results on the same dataset. Accurate characterization of ENSO is critical for understanding the trends and potential impacts such as droughts, floods, and tropical storms. In this course, I have explored using deep learning to improve the forecasting accuracy of ENSO.

1. 2.Data

After a literature review and consulting Dr. Lang Chiu. I have decided to use Southern Oscillation Index (SOI) to represent the ENSO process. Four other climate variables have been identified to be related to ENSO: Oceanic Nino Index (ONI), Eastern Tropical Pacific SST (Nino 3), Pacific North American Index (PNA), and precipitation monthly mean. Specifically, they are retrieved from the following locations:

- SOI: [https://crudata.uea.ac.uk/cru/data/soi/soi\_3dp.dat](https://crudata.uea.ac.uk/cru/data/soi/soi_3dp.dat)
- ONI: [http://origin.cpc.ncep.noaa.gov/products/analysis\_monitoring/ensostuff/ONI\_v5.php](http://origin.cpc.ncep.noaa.gov/products/analysis_monitoring/ensostuff/ONI_v5.php)
- Nino 3: [https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/gcos\_wgsp/Timeseries/Nino3/](https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/gcos_wgsp/Timeseries/Nino3/)
- PNA: [https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/data/correlation/pna.data](https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/data/correlation/pna.data)
- Precipitation: [https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/data/gridded/data.gpcp.html](https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/data/gridded/data.gpcp.html)



1. 3.Methods, results, and evaluation

In this study, ENSO forecasting is simplified as predicting SOI values for the next three consecutive month. Three major steps were performed in order to predict SOI:

- Data exploration via Fast Fourier Transformation and autocorrelation
- Correlation analysis between SOI and other variables with different lags
- Comparison of the results of RNN/LSTM, multiple output linear regression, and random forest

The code has been put into Ipython notebook on Github, which can be found here: [https://github.com/Yongyao/enso-forcasting/tree/master/inotebook](https://github.com/Yongyao/enso-forcasting/tree/master/inotebook)

1.
  1. 3.2Correlation analysis

First, I looked at the correlation (lag = 0) between all these 5 five variables through Figure 4. It turns out SOI has strong correlation with ONI, slightly less strong correlation with Nino 3 and Precipitation, weak correlation with PNA.



 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 4. Correlation heatmap

Then, I examined the correlation between SOI and the other four variables with different lags (1-12). Figure 5 shows that there is a downward trend from lag 1 to 12 for ONI, Nino 3, and Precipitation. The correlation for PNA has some ups and downs, but overall the correlation is relatively weak. This finding can guide us to choose an appropriate lag in the modeling process.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 5. Correlation between SOI and the others with different lags (1-12)

1.
  1. 3.3Model comparison

As a prior step, I&#39;ve converted the ENSO data into standard supervised machine learning format by set lag as 12 and ahead as 3, meaning I would use the past 12 months&#39; data to predict the next 3 months&#39; SOI. Figure 6 shows the first 5 rows of the converted data.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 6. The first 5 rows of the converted data

Long Short Term Memory network (LSTM) is a special kind of recurrent neural network (RNN), capable of learning long-term dependencies. A LSTM was then trained with the data. In order to benchmark the performance, a multiple output linear regression model and a random forest model were also trained with the same data. According to Figure 7 and Table 1, the linear regression model surprisingly performs the best and the LSTM model does not show significant improvement over the other two methods.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 7. Comparing the observed SOI with the prediction (the right charts are the closer looks of the left ones)

Table 1. Root mean squared error of the three algorithms at different time steps

|   | **LSTM** | **Linear regression** | **Random forest** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| T | 0.79 | 0.67 | 0.72 |
| T+1 | 0.84 | 0.73 | 0.82 |
| T+2 | 0.90 | 0.77 | 0.83 |

1. 4.Conclusion and discussion

This study explores using deep/machine learning to improve the forecasts of ENSO. Experimental results show that although LSTM does not show substantial improvement over the traditional methods, machine learning can be a useful technique for such purpose. In order to improve the performance, further investigation is need in several directions.

- Tune the LSTM. Grid search some of the LSTM parameters used in the tutorial, such as number of epochs, number of neurons, and number of layers to see if you can further lift performance.
- Use the encoder-decoder paradigm for LSTMs to forecast each sequence to see if this offers any benefit.
- Time Horizon. Experiment with forecasting different time horizons and see how the behavior of the network varies at different lead times.
- Add more training data. Perhaps it&#39;s worth trying to remove the precipitation variable and start from 1951.
